description: From Middle English transcenden, from Old French transcender, from Latin transcendere (“to climb over, step over, surpass, transcend”), from trans (“over”) + scandere (“to climb”); see scan; compare ascend, descend.

verbs.description: transcend (third-person singular simple present transcends, present participle transcending, simple past and past participle transcended)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To pass beyond the limits of something.
(transitive) To surpass, as in intensity or power; to excel.
examples: How much her worth transcended all her kind.
lights in the heavens transcending the region of the clouds
